title: Customizable Bracelet - Choose your own colours, print then link together and wear!.

description.text:
This customizable bracelet has two parts... a block and a link. Print each component in the number and colour or choice to create a unique 3D printed bracelet.   
Links are added and removed by rotating one component 90° from the other then sliding the link to the centre of the block and inserting/extracting it.   
Build up your bracelet by printing blocks and links in the colours and numbers of choice. Easy to link together, easy to put on and remove, but it won't come off until you want it to as it requires a link/block to rotate a full 90° to link/unlink.   
A simple but effective way to create a unique and colourful 3D printed bracelet. Glow in the dark filament is also very effective.

Both parts print really well on a Replicator 2 with a Raft, 4 shells and 35% infill. No support required. The .stl's are for single pieces. Copy and paste as many as you need to make the required length (13 to 15 blocks should cover most wrist sizes).

I wanted to create a couple mounts for my snowboards so i could mount them to the wall in my room. Very simple to setup.

Phillips screw driver
Level
Pencil Hardware needed: If mounting to studs you can use #8 x 2 - 1/2 in screws to mount to the wall. I would also use some washers If mounting to drywall you will have to use some drywall anchors and using #8 x 2 - 1/2 in screws to mount the snowboard wall mounts. Link to the drywall Anchor kit that I used: http://www.homedepot.com/p/Zip-It-8-Nylon-Anchor-with-Screw-20-Pack-376229/202243022 Enjoy

comments.text: Just printing a set of these now, love the design and the only suggestion I have is that the wall mount side with the screw holes could be extended a small amount and the screws placed under one another. If you're trying to mount this to a standard wooden wall the screws are 1" apart leaving just 1/4" on either side to grab a standard 2x4 or 2x4 which is only 1 1/2" wide. Having them one under the other would allow the screws to sink directly into the center of the stud. Course these are great if you're mounting in any other medium.

description.text: I need swivels that can quickly be attached to other things that have the matching notch in them. This thing has a key that fits into a notch, like the notches on this thing: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:5874 What would you do with it? Attach this thing to something else. Then put a 5/16" (M8) rod through the holes. It can swivel freely, so you've just made an easy mounting axle. Now attach interesting other things to the axle, and there you go! This thing has some mounting holes (M3) for those who like mounting holes. Otherwise, a good friction fit will work for most uses. In the OpenScad file, you can change anything, from the size of the key to the size of the holes for the axle. A good thing to do might be to increase the size of the axle holes, and put small bearings in there for a nice smooth ride.

1) Print a few of these
2) Slip them into matching notches on your design
3) Slip a piece of axle material through the loops (wood, steel bar, carbon fiber tubing...)
4) Attach other stuff to the axles
5) Rejoice!

=========== 2x motor bases with fixed motor

1x control deck Part list
=======
  • printed parts
  • vibration dampers (6 pcs)
  • plastic standoffs (4 pcs)
  • motors for 250 size racing quads (3 pcs) (such as DYS BE1806 2300KV)
  • 15A ESC (3pcs) (such as AfroSlim)
  • 9g servo
  • control board
  • 6 inch props (6030)
  • R/C transmitter and receiver
  • M3 screws & lock nuts
  • Battery (such as ZippyCompact 1800mAh) - check dimensions. It has to fit on main deck.
    • Assembly
    ========
  • use M3 screws to join all bases together (delta shape)
  • install servo (do not forget to get it centered)
  • install tail motor part (2 mm dia axis 10-15 mm length on both sides is fine)

  • fix servo arm to tail motor part (to the flap)

  • use plastic standoffs to connect control and main deck. The battery has to fit between those decks

  • stick control boart to control deck using double sided tape (or simply drill holes and screw it)

  • install vibradion dampers and join motor part with main deck

  • install motors and ESCs (ESCs should fit under motor bases)

  • add R/C

  • connect everything to control board
    • Note: Small "hole" on upper and control deck is CG mark.

description.text: Motorized version of Rudolf Reigns (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:580020) with additions (never waste a good PTO, also, I can convert this to hand cranked if anyone desires). Video of prototype is here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rs5yVL5QmpI&list=UUv_zm49u-RjnCJVwhUO-ecA. UPDATE: "Assembly.skp" has been updated such that it now includes an exploded view of the assembly. Thanks to Thingiverse member Alzibiff for discovering my error. Designed using Sketchup Make 2015, and printed in PLA on a Makerbot Replicator 2 using Makerware 2.3.3.42 "Standard" (.2mm layer height, 2 shells, 10% infill) settings.

Parts I purchased:  
1) 6VDC 45 RPM Pinky Finger Sized Gear Motor 1" Long x 15/32" x 3/8" (amazon).  
2) Coaxial Power Jack (Radio Shack part number 274-1583).  
3) 3.0 Vdc Power Supply (Radio Shack part number 273-315 with the "N" style plug 273-345, you get one free with the power supply).  
Study "Assembly.skp".  
Print all pieces as shown in "Assembly.skp".  
Test fit and trim, file, sand, etc. all parts as necessary for smooth movement of moving surfaces, and tight fit for non moving surfaces. Depending on the colors you chose and your printer settings, more or less trimming, filing and/or sanding will be required.  
Assemble as per "Assembly.skp", paying close attention to the gear and eccentric alignment. When installing each "Gear.stl" into "Base.stl", carefully pry apart the gear block tower to slide the gear in place, again, paying close attention to the gear alignment as indicated in "Assembly.skp". It is best to start at either end, then install the gears toward the opposite end.  
Wiring is pretty straight forward, however you'll need soldering skills and equipment. Basically, solder a 4" red wire between the gear motor "plus" terminal and the coaxial power jack "Center" terminal, then solder a 4" black wire between the gear motor "minus" terminal and the coaxial power jack "Shield" terminal. Make sure the wires do not interfere with moving components.  
Lubricate moving surfaces with light machine oil.  
Comment if questions.  
Hope you like it!

This idea is based on Gav's Z-Probe, but this version is mounted outside of the build area and does not require running the axis so far past the point where it would normally collide with the platform. Instead of icky glue and scrap acrylic, it uses a smaller board-mount microswitch mounted to the z-guide screws with a bit of perf board and some left-over standoffs. This version makes it possible to home all three axes without X/Y endstops (though they are recommended, and it makes terrible noises without them).

Here's my homing gcode: ( 3-axis homing with a z probe on the back-right leadscrew nut )
G91 (relative Positioning)
G0 Z10 (raise Z stage to clear the switch)
G0 X0 Y150 (move Y axis to the back)
G0 X150 Y0 (move X axis to the far right)
G0 Z-50 (lower Z until hits limit)
G92 Z0 (Set current point as Z-origin)
G0 Z6.5 (raise Z to clear screws)
G0 X-66.5 Y-50 (move build platform to middle of table, use X-63.5 with ABP)
G0 Z-10 (touch the table)
G92 X0 Y0 Z0 (Set current point as origin)
G90 (switch back to absolute positioning)
( Honey! I'm home! )
